The decision to graduate in two years was practical: my sister began college immediately after I finished my undergraduate degree, and completing my degree earlier eased my family's financial burden. The pressure to graduate early pushed me to take a large course load in my undergraduate studies alongside commitments to clubs and research. These challenges taught me to be resourceful. It forced me to identify opportunities quickly, build relationships with mentors, and seek out communities where I could learn from others. Graduating early while maintaining my research and community commitments shaped my approach to navigating challenges. I believe these same qualities will aid me as a graduate student.

Managing coursework while pursuing research, founding the Algorithms Club, and participating in competitive programming often required persistence. Although it sometimes spread me thin, working on various projects helped me gain perspective on each one, and to grow in them very quickly. One of the most valuable parts of my undergraduate study was meeting people with different academic backgrounds in research and through running the club, and seeing how different collaborators offered unique perspectives. In both my research and the Algorithms Club, I saw how different approaches to problems and reading papers led to better discussions and insights. In each club meeting, we read papers in both new and familiar areas of theoretical computer science, forcing us to engage with new content. These discussions exposed us all to new ideas and influenced my approach to research. In the Multimodal Interactions Lab, I also introduced new students to HCI literature and research tools, helping them explore the field. 

In the Algorithms Club, I worked to make theoretical computer science accessible to students from computer science, mathematics, and other engineering disciplines. Working with people who from different academic backgrounds and with different research interests often led to productive research discussions by challenging us to view the work through a different lens. As a graduate student, I'm eager to continue working with people across subdisciplines within theoretical computer science, to mentor students encountering new research areas, and to help create inclusive problem-solving communities. I believe that the persistence I developed through my coursework and commitments and my research alongside others who challenge my thinking will help me be successful in graduate study.

